article.headline: Johnson's OT jumper ends run at five
article.linkText: Back to Earth: Suns snap Rockets' streak
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- The Houston Rockets fell into the Phoenix Suns' trapping defense once again and Joe Johnson slammed the door. Johnson made a 16-foot fadeaway jumper with 1.4 seconds to play in overtime and the Phoenix Suns snapped the Houston Rockets' five-game winning streak, 99-97 Monday night. Shawn Marion had 17 of his 29 points in the second half as the Suns rallied from 21 points down in the second quarter and overcame a big performance by Yao Ming, who had 29 points, 19 rebounds and six blocked shots. "I knew that the clock was running down," Johnson said of his game-winner. "The coach told us he didn't want to give them more than two seconds so I was watching the clock. Then, I saw Yao backing up so I just faded away for a jump shot." The Suns' trapping defense slowly took its toll on the Rockets, who committed 27 turnovers, 11 in the third quarter when the Suns really started to rally. "The trap on our full-court press really bothered them," Suns coach Mike D'Antoni said. "They struggled against it when we played them in the past and they've also struggled against small lineups." Phoenix took their first lead, 67-65, with 56 seconds left in the third quarter on a pair of free throws by Zarko Cabarkapa. "The whole thing is after playing bad the last two nights and after the way we played in the first quarter, this team really sucked it up," D'Antoni said. Trailing 73-70 with 8:53 to play in regulation, Houston used a 9-0 run to regain the lead with 6:27 to go. Yao scored six points during the spurt. The Suns regained the lead at 81-79 but Yao scored on a dunk, two free throws, and after a 3-point basket by Jackson, a 20-foot jumper for an 88-83 lead. But the Suns wouldn't quit. A jumper by Johnson and a three-point play by Amare Stoudemire pulled Phoenix within three, and Marion drilled a 3-pointer with 6 seconds left in regulation for the tie. "Yao played great but he got a lot of easy baskets," Stoudemire said. "We just stuck with it and played some hard defense against him. It's tough. He's 7-6 and I'm 6-9, trying to block his shots. He's already at the rim. I thought I did a pretty good job against him." Houston got its final lead in overtime on a driving layup by Cuttino Mobley with 38 seconds to play for a 96-95 lead. Stoudemire's basket put the Suns ahead and Yao made a free throw to tie it 97-all. "We played awful after the first quarter," Rockets coach Jeff Van Gundy said. "It's inexcusable to coach that way and not have your team where they should be. We had chances to finish the game. It's a bad loss." The Rockets got a big early lead on the 3-point shooting of Jim Jackson, who finished with 23 points and hit seven of eight from 3-point range. Mobley had 20 points and Steve Francis had 12. The Rockets shot 13-of-25 for 3-pointers. Stoudemire scored 24 points and Johnson finished with 19. The Rockets led 48-35 at the half. Stoudemire and Francis drew double technicals for a brief confrontation with 8:07 to go in the third quarter. Officials declined comment after the game.

Game notes
The Rockets play 11 of their final 16 games on the road. They are 14-16 away from home this season. ... The Rockets are 25-11 at home and had a seven-game winning streak in Toyota Center snapped. ... The Rockets are 31-10 when leading at the half. ... Clarence Weatherspoon missed his second straight game with a sprained left ankle. ... Shawn Marion is on pace to join Dick Van Arsdale and Dan Majerle as the only Suns players to play 3,000 minutes in a season three times. Only 15 Suns players have recorded 3,000 minutes in a season one time. ... Maurice Taylor sat out the game with strained ribs.
